	affiliations = {Department of Computer Engineering, Vidya Pratishthan’s Kamalnayan Bajaj Institute of Engineering and Technology, Maharashtra, Baramati, Pune, 413133, India; M.D. Research, Intervention Treatment Institute, Houston, TX, United States; Software Engineer, Alphabet Life Science, Dallas, 75063, TX, United States; Model Institute of Engineering and Technology, J&K, Jammu, India; Department of Computer Science and Mathematics, Lebanese American University, Beirut, Lebanon; Symbiosis Law School (SLS), Symbiosis International (Deemed University) (SIU), Maharashtra, Vimannagar, Pune, India; Computer Science and Information Systems Department, College of Applied Sciences, AlMaarefa University, Riyadh, Saudi Arabia; Dr D Y Patil Vidyapeeth, Dr. D. Y. Patil School of Science and Technology, Pune, 411033, India; Department of Digital Anti-Aging Healthcare, Inje University, Gimhae, 50834, South Korea},
	abstract = {Emerging from the convergence of digital twin technology and the metaverse, consumer health (MCH) is witnessing a transformative shift. The amalgamation of bioinformatics with healthcare Big Data has ushered in a new era of disease prediction models that harness comprehensive medical data, enabling the anticipation of illnesses even before the onset of symptoms. In this model, deep neural networks stand out because they improve accuracy remarkably by increasing network depth and making weight changes using gradient descent. Nonetheless, traditional methods face their own set of challenges, including the issues of gradient instability and slow training. In this case, the Broad Learning System (BLS) stands out as a good alternative. It gets around the problems with gradient descent and lets you quickly rebuild a model through incremental learning. One problem with BLS is that it has trouble extracting complex features from complex medical data. This makes it less useful in a wide range of healthcare situations. In response to these challenges, we introduce DAE-BLS, a novel hybrid model that marries Denoising AutoEncoder (DAE) noise reduction with the efficiency of BLS. This hybrid approach excels in robust feature extraction, particularly within the intricate and multifaceted world of medical data. Validation using diverse datasets yields impressive results, with accuracies reaching as high as 98.50%. DAE-BLS’s ability to rapidly adapt through incremental learning holds great promise for accurate and agile disease prediction, especially within the complex and dynamic healthcare scenarios of today. © The Author(s) 2024.},
	author_keywords = {Bioinformatics; Deep neural networks; Digital twin; Disease prediction; Healthcare},
	keywords = {Big Data; Computational Biology; Health Facilities; Humans; Neural Networks, Computer; Technology; artificial neural network; big data; bioinformatics; health care facility; human; technology},
